<DOC><DOCNO> AP891019-0012 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-19-89 0049EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-USList     10-19 0358</FIRST><SECOND>PM-SF Quake-US List,0388</SECOND><HEAD>List of Deadliest U.S. Quakes</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-SF Quake Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Tuesday's earthquake was the second deadliest in U.S. history.Here is a list of major quakes as recorded by the U. S. GeologicalSurvey:</TEXT><NOTE>SAN FRANCISCO, APRIL 18-19, 1906</NOTE><TEXT>   Rated at 8.3 on the Richter scale. Ruptured gas lines,overturned stoves, started fires that destroyed much of the city,killing hundreds. Traditional estimates put the death toll at 500to 700, but the city archivist recently established that at least2,500, and possibly 5,000 people were killed.</TEXT><NOTE>SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, OCT. 17, 1989</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading 6.9. Collapsed a mile of double-deck highway,inflicted widespread damage to buildings. Struck at evening rushhour. At least 272 people dead and 650 injured, according to earlyofficial reports.</TEXT><NOTE>PRINCE WILLIAM SOUND, ALASKA, MARCH 27, 1964</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading 8.4. The infamous Good Friday Earthquake. Therewere 131 deaths and extensive damage in Alaska.</TEXT><NOTE>MONA PASSAGE, PUERTO RICO, OCT. 11, 1918</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading 7.5. Shook the Mona Passage between Puerto Ricoand the island of Hispaniola. Some 116 people died, many in thegiant wave generated by the quake.</TEXT><NOTE>LONG BEACH, CALIF., MARCH 10, 1933</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading 6.2. Hit a heavily populated area. Manybuildings collapsed, including schools, and 115 people died.Brought about wide revision of building codes, including standardsrequiring new buildings to withstand lateral forces fromearthquakes.</TEXT><NOTE>SAN FERNANDO VALLEY, CALIF., FEB. 9, 1971</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading of 6.4. Killed 65 people, 45 of them in thecollapse of a Veterans Administration hospital at Sylmar. Totaldamage unofficially estimated at $600 million, with at least $37million to highways, streets and bridges. Outside of areas nearestthe epicenter, principal damage involved buildings erected 40 ormore years earlier.</TEXT><NOTE>CHARLESTON, S.C., AUG. 31, 1886</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading of 6.6. Killed 60 people. Was felt for a radiusof 1,000 miles, as far away as Boston, Milwaukee and Havana, Cuba.</TEXT><NOTE>HEBGEN LAKE, MONT., AUG. 17, 1959</NOTE><TEXT>   Richter reading of 7.3. Was felt from Seattle to North Dakota toUtah. Extensive damage was reported and 28 people died.</TEXT></DOC>